article.description:
Sheri Sam had seven of her 11 points in the second half to help the Miami Sol hang on for a 61-58 victory over
Minnesota on Friday night, the Lynx's seventh straight loss.
article.headline: Lynx keep it close, but lose seventh straight
article.linkText: Sol survive to win again vs. lowly Lynx
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Sheri Sam had seven of her 11 points in the
second half to help the Miami Sol hang on for a 61-58 victory over
Minnesota on Friday night, the Lynx's seventh straight loss.

	   Katie Smith led the Lynx with 12 points, but her chance to tie
the game on a 3-pointer with 2 seconds left was an airball.

	   "We got the shot we were looking for,'' Minnesota interim coach
Heidi Vanderveer said. "I'd give Katie Smith the ball there 10
times, and I bet she'd make nine of them.''

	   Betty Lennox had 10 points on 7-for-20 and seven rebounds
against her old team for the Sol, who have won eight of 10 since
starting the season 2-9.

	   "We're not blowing people away, but we're managing,'' Sol coach
Ron Rothstein said.

	   Sandy Brondello added 11 points -- nine in the first half -- for
Miami, which stayed a half-game behind Orlando for the fourth and
final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference.

	   Tamika Williams had 11 points for the Lynx, while reserve Janell
Burse had all 10 of her points in the first half.

	   With Minnesota trailing by nine, Tamara Moore and Shaunzinski
Gortman hit consecutive 3-pointers to bring the Lynx within three.
Lennox missed a 3-pointer with 13 seconds left, setting up Smith's
chance to tie it.

	   Lennox was 0-for-6 from 3-point range.

	   "That's the great part about being on this team,'' she said.
"I know what my job is -- to go out and shoot.''

	   Lennox was the starting point guard for the Lynx until she was
benched and then traded to the Sol for Moore last month. She didn't
leave Minnesota on the best terms -- criticizing coach and general
manager Brian Agler for "betraying'' her.

	   But Agler, who resigned from his coaching duties this week,
wasn't around for Lennox to prove he made the wrong move.
Vanderveer, who took over the team Tuesday, fell to 0-2 as interim
coach.

	   Lennox, the WNBA's Rookie of the Year with the Lynx in 2000,
entered the game early in the first half and was greeted with a
hearty ovation from the announced crowd of 5,370 -- many of them
wearing green Lynx jerseys bearing Lennox's name and No. 22.

	   Since the June 11 trade, the Sol are 9-6 and the Lynx are 3-12.

	   "It shows they miss me and still give me support here,'' Lennox
said, adding that she hoped the Lynx wished she was still around.
"I'm not a bad person.''
